-*- mode: org -*-

* About

GNU Agent-Zero Genesis is a hypergraphically-encoded cognitive OS environment
built on top of Guile-Daemon, designed for autonomous cognitive agents using
GNU Guix, Guile, and cognitive computing frameworks.

Agent-Zero Genesis extends the original Guile-Daemon with:

- **Cognitive Kernels**: Tensor-based processing units with prime factorization encoding
- **Hypergraph AtomSpace**: OpenCog-inspired knowledge representation
- **ECAN Attention Networks**: Economic Cognitive Attention allocation
- **Meta-Cognitive Loops**: Recursive self-description and adaptation
- **Distributed Cognition**: Multi-agent coordination and communication

The system provides a FIFO-based interface for cognitive commands and
supports socket connections for interactive development with tools like Geiser.

Core cognitive subsystems:
- **Memory**: AtomSpace hypergraph store, persistent cognitive states
- **Task**: Scheduler, MOSES optimizer, agent orchestration
- **AI**: PLN reasoning, ECAN attention, pattern matching  
- **Autonomy**: Self-modifying kernels, adaptive package selection

By default, socket and FIFO files are placed in
[[file:$XDG_CONFIG_HOME/guile-daemon/run]] directory
([[file:$HOME/.config/guile-daemon/run]] if XDG_CONFIG_HOME is not set).

* Quick Start

** Agent-Zero Genesis Setup

The fastest way to get started with Agent-Zero Genesis:

#+BEGIN_SRC sh
# Clone and setup
git clone https://github.com/ZoneCog/guile-daemon-zero.git
cd guile-daemon-zero
./scripts/setup-agent-zero.sh
#+END_SRC

** Manual Setup with Guix

#+BEGIN_SRC sh
# Create Agent-Zero environment
export AGENT_ZERO_MANIFEST=1
guix environment -m guix.scm

# Build the system
./autogen.sh
./configure --enable-cognitive-extensions  
make

# Start Agent-Zero cognitive daemon
./pre-inst-env guile-daemon &

# Send cognitive commands
./pre-inst-env gdpipe '(use-modules (agent-zero))'
./pre-inst-env gdpipe '(spawn-agent-zero (load-agent-zero-config "agent-zero-config.scm"))'
#+END_SRC

* Cognitive Agent Usage

Simply run =guile-daemon= with Agent-Zero extensions, then use =gdpipe= 
to interact with the cognitive system:

#+BEGIN_SRC sh
# Start cognitive daemon
guile-daemon --config agent-zero-config.scm &

# Spawn cognitive kernels
gdpipe '(use-modules (agent-zero kernel))'
gdpipe '(spawn-cognitive-kernel (64 64) logical-reasoning 0.8)'

# Create hypergraph knowledge
gdpipe '(use-modules (agent-zero hypergraph))'  
gdpipe '(let ((as (make-atomspace)))
          (atomspace-add-node! as "ConceptNode" "intelligence")
          (atomspace-add-node! as "ConceptNode" "agent-zero"))'

# Apply attention allocation
gdpipe '(use-modules (agent-zero attention))'
gdpipe '(let ((net (make-attention-network)))
          (allocate-attention! net kernels stimuli))'
#+END_SRC

Agent-Zero Genesis can be used for:
- Cognitive computing research
- AI agent development  
- Hypergraph knowledge representation
- Attention-based reasoning systems
- Meta-cognitive architectures

** Cognitive Computing Packages

Agent-Zero now includes Guix package definitions for cognitive computing
frameworks:

- **OpenCog**: Hypergraph knowledge representation and cognitive algorithms
- **OpenCog AtomSpace**: Core hypergraph database for AGI research
- **GGML**: High-performance tensor operations for machine learning

To validate the package definitions:
#+BEGIN_SRC sh
./scripts/validate-cognitive-packages.sh
#+END_SRC

See [[file:doc/COGNITIVE-PACKAGES.md]] for detailed package documentation
and [[file:AGENT-ZERO-GENESIS.md]] for comprehensive development guide.

* Building from Git

Requirements for building from git:

- [[http://gnu.org/software/guile/][GNU Guile]]
- [[http://gnu.org/software/autoconf/][GNU Autoconf]]
- [[http://gnu.org/software/automake/][GNU Automake]]

Run =./autogen.sh= to generate the build system infrastructure.  After
that, the program can be built and installed with the usual sequence of
commands of the GNU Build System:

#+BEGIN_SRC sh
$ ./configure
$ make
# make install
#+END_SRC

** Pre-installation environment

It is possible to use/test Guile-Daemon without installing (i.e., after
running =make= but before running =make install=) with the help of
=pre-inst-env= script in the top build tree, like this:

#+BEGIN_SRC sh
$ ./pre-inst-env guile-daemon &
$ ./pre-inst-env gdpipe ...
#+END_SRC

If you live in Emacs, you may find =pre-inst-env.el= more useful.  If
you load this file (for example, with =M-x load-file=), it will set the
required environment inside Emacs, so you can run =guile-daemon= and
=gdpipe= in =M-x shell= without prefixing them with =.../pre-inst-env=.
And more importantly, you can start Geiser and use (daemon ...) modules
there!

* Building/installing with Guix

The latest version of Guile-Daemon can be installed with [[http://www.gnu.org/software/guix/][GNU Guix]]:
[[https://www.gnu.org/software/guix/packages/g.html#guile-daemon]].

Also this repository contains [[file:guix.scm]] file which can be used to
build/install Guile-Daemon using the git checkout, or to make a
development environment for it (see the commentary in that file for more
details).
